This is impossible if the data propagation is not nested in nature, for example in [`typeslot`](https://github.com/voxell-tech/typeslot) (a crate that I maintain) each generic variant `Foo<f32>, Foo<u32>, Foo<i32>` needs to be assigned a different index that does not clash with each other, so having a trait with `f32`/`u32`/`i32` doesn't help here.

Even worse, because of the orphan rule, you'll have to create a new type for every instance if you are using `typeslot` in a library!

For example in [`fynix`](https://github.com/voxell-tech/fynix), `typeslot` is used to create a unique index for each element type. If we were to create a generic element `Element<T>`, we have to register every variant of `T` ourselves.

