Thanks for the prompt response. To address your comments:

> @zesterer I don't think this is a problem with streams specifically: a very similar problem occurs with async implementations of basic concurrency primitives like mutexes and read-write locks which do not rely on the `Stream` trait at all.

Yes, this is a subtle and general problem that needs to be accounted for with futures. However, it becomes a particular acute problem with streams, because they, just as with iterators, may commonly be passed around with values only extracted on occasion. The same is *not* usually the case with futures because they are usually polled in-place. What makes this worse is that the behaviour is inconsistent. This might work fine for some kinds of streams that do not do concurrent access, but will break entirely for others.

At the very least, optional methods on `Stream` with an empty default impl like `thaw` and `freeze` that might be called by users of the stream to indicate a lack of interest in items being pulled would provide the potential for significant improvements in performance for certain cases (something that simply cannot be done with the current implementation) while also improving the correctness of functions like `StreamExt::next`.

Alternatively, an extension trait like `trait PausableStream: Stream {}` that is required for the implementation of non-contiguous polling of items such as that which occurs when using `StreamExt::next` intermittently would help to alleviate this problem, provided third-party crates like `futures` adhered to it.

> In general, it can happen any time you have an async construct that is accessed by more than two threads. In these situations the construct itself needs a way to drive progress without relying on one of the threads calling poll on some method (since that is not guaranteed to happen promptly).

This relies on either significant usage overhead for the user of the future, or the future itself having fairly close contact with the runtime (via a function like `task::spawn`) in order to ensure that progress is made. The former is an ugly and undesirable thing to require in an API and the latter breaks runtime-agnostic abstractions and comes with notable overhead.

> In your MPMC channel example where you want to be able to stop receiving for a while, you would pass around a `Handle` to the channel, and only construct a `Receiver` from that handle when you want to start receving items. You would drop it when you want to stop. (And you can use the normal "close" + "keep receiving until end" pattern to ensure no items are lost when you want to stop receiving). This does not require changes to the `Stream` trait: you just shouldn't construct the type implementing `Stream` until ready to actually receive.

As mentioned above, this is not something that can be solved from within the crate: it requires users to consciously avoid using the API in a manner that is suggestive of the API (`Stream` and `Iterator` appear superficially to occupy the same design space). If nothing else, this impedes potential usages of `Stream`. I think I'd probably err on the side of caution by not implementing `Stream` for a channel receiver - even via a handle - to avoid this case accidentally arising.

EDIT: Instead of the current proposal, I'd suggest instead an API like this:

```rust
// Defined in std::stream module
pub trait Stream {
    // Core items:
    type Item;
    
    // Must be called before any calls to `poll_next`.
    fn start_polling(&mut self) {}
    
    // May be called any number of times between calls to `start_polling` and `end_polling`.
    // A best attempt should be made to call `end_polling` if the stream is likely to not be polled for some time.
    fn poll_next(self: Pin<&mut Self>, cx: &mut Context<'_>) -> Poll<Option<Self::Item>>;
    
    // Must be called after a series of calls to `poll_next`.
    fn end_polling(&mut self) {}
    
    // Optional optimization hint, just like with iterators:
    #[inline]
    fn size_hint(&self) -> (usize, Option<usize>) {
        (0, None)
    }
}
```

`StreamExt::next`'s future would then be implemented like so:

```rust
struct Next<S> {
    stream: S,
    started: bool,
}

impl<S: Stream> Future for Next<S> {
    type Output = Option<S::Item>;

    fn poll(self: Pin<&mut Self>, cx: &mut Context) -> Poll<Option<S::Item>> {
        if !self.started {
            self.stream.start_polling();
            self.started = true;
        }
        // Todo: Prevent polling after future has already completed (trivially implementable)
        let item = match self.stream.poll_next(cx) { 
            Poll::Ready(item) => item,
            Poll::Pending => return Poll::Pending,
        };
        self.stream.end_polling();
        item
    }
}
```

This would allow many implementations of `Stream` to be significantly more efficient and also logically more correct (i.e: not freezing queues or similar such behaviour) while having zero overhead or implementation baggage for streams that do not make use of it.

This is not a total solution to the problems I listed above, but it's a significant step in the right direction, in my view.

